<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Overview">Overview</span></h2>
<p>By the end of this tutorial you will have a translucent reflective water material which can be used as a master material to be instanced throughout your projects and levels. We will create parameters so when using the instance you can quickly change the look and feel of your water to suit your needs.
</p>
<pre>    <i>This tutorial assumes the user has a basic understanding of the Material Editor.</i> 
    <i>Creating comments wherever possible is very helpful to understanding how the material functions!</i>
</pre>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Final_Outcome">Final Outcome</span></h3>
<div class="thumb tleft"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:1076px;"><a href="/File:RealisticWater.PNG" class="image"><img alt="" src="https://d26ilriwvtzlb.cloudfront.net/4/47/RealisticWater.PNG" width="1074" height="789" class="thumbimage" /></a>  <div class="thumbcaption">Final Outcome of Water Material</div></div></div>
<p><br clear="all" />
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Texture_Files">Texture Files</span></h3>
<p>For this tutorial we will be using the “T_Ground_Grass” normal texture sample from the starter content as our ripples/waves.
</p><p><br />
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Steps_to_Follow">Steps to Follow</span></h3>
<p>Follow these steps in order to complete the tutorial!
</p><p><br />
</p>
<h4><span class="mw-headline" id="Diffuse_Section">Diffuse Section</span></h4>
<p>1. So to begin let us create a new material in the content browser and name it whatever you would like. You can always rename it later as you see fit. In my example I am using the name “M_ExteriorLiquid.”
</p><p>2. Create two “Constant3Vector” nodes.
</p>
<pre>    a. One color will represent our lighter water color and the other the darker water color.
    b. Use the image posted as a reference for the colors used.
    c. Convert these vectors into parameter by right-clicking and choose “Convert to parameter.”
</pre>
<p>3. Now create a “Fresnel” by right-clicking in an empty space and typing the word into the search field.
</p>
<pre>    a. Set the “Exponent” to 5.0
    b. Set the “Base Reflect Fraction to 1.0
</pre>
<p>4. Next create a linear interpolation or “Lerp” for short. The keyboard shortcut for this is holding the “L” key and left-mouse click.
</p>
<pre>    a. Connect the Dark Color to the “A”
    b. Connect the Light Color to the “B”
    c. Connect the Fresnel to the “Alpha”
</pre>
<p>5. Create two constants and convert these both to parameters as well.
</p>
<pre>    a. Name one “Fresnel Parameter” and connect it to the “ExponentIn” of the “Fresnel” node.
    b. Name the other “Diffuse Multiply”
</pre>
<p>6. Now we need to create a “Depth Fade” node.
</p>
<pre>    a. Set the “Opacity Default” to 1.0
    b. Set the “Fade Distance Default” to 500.0
</pre>
<p>7. Create two “Multiply” nodes. Keyboard shortcut is to hold “M” and left-mouse click.
</p>
<pre>    a. Connect the “Lerp” to the “A”
    b. Connect the “Depth Fade” to “B”
</pre>
<p>8. Now connect the outcome of that “Multiply” to the input of the “B” of the second “Multiply.”
</p><p>9. Connect the “Diffuse Multiply” to the “A”
</p><p>10. Connect the outcome of the second “Multiply” to the “Base Color” of the Material.
</p><p>11. Create an external “Multiply” outside of your diffuse section.
</p>
<pre>    a. Connect this to the “A”
    b. We will combine this with the Opacity/Refraction and Normal Multiply and plug this into our “Specular” for our material
</pre>
<p>12. Create two “Constant” vectors and convert them to parameters.
</p>
<pre>    a. Name one Metallic
       i. Set value to 1
       ii. Connect to the “Metallic” of our material
    b. Name one “Roughness”
       i. Set value to .08
       ii. Connect to the “Roughness of our material
</pre>
<div class="thumb tleft"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:1098px;"><a href="/File:Diffuse_Section.PNG" class="image"><img alt="" src="https://d26ilriwvtzlb.cloudfront.net/8/84/Diffuse_Section.PNG" width="1096" height="632" class="thumbimage" /></a>  <div class="thumbcaption">Diffuse Section</div></div></div>
<p><br clear="all" />
</p>
<h4><span class="mw-headline" id="Opacity_and_Refraction_Section">Opacity and Refraction Section</span></h4>
<p>Here we will set the Opacity and Refraction of our water.
</p>
<pre>    <i>Before we can do that we need to set our materials “Blend Mode” to “Translucent.” Click on the material node to view these properties.</i>
    
    <i>Under the “Translucency” section of your material uncheck “Separate Translucency” and within “Translucency Lighting Mode” select “TLM Surface.”</i>
    
    <i>Within the “Usage” section check the options “Used with Fluid Surfaces” and “Uses Distortion.”</i>
</pre>
<div class="thumb tleft"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:912px;"><a href="/File:MaterialDetails.PNG" class="image"><img alt="" src="https://d26ilriwvtzlb.cloudfront.net/6/64/MaterialDetails.PNG" width="910" height="322" class="thumbimage" /></a>  <div class="thumbcaption">Material Details</div></div></div>
<p><br clear="all" />
</p><p>1. Create two new “Multiply” nodes.
</p><p>2. Create a “Depth Fade” node.
</p><p>3. Create a “Fresnel” node.
</p><p>4. Create two “Constant” nodes and convert them into parameters.
</p>
<pre>    a. Name one “Refraction”
       i. Set this value to 2.0
    b. Name one “Fresnel Parameter”
       i. Set this value to 0.2
</pre>
<p>5. Create a “1-x” node or “One Minus” node.
</p><p>6. Set the “Depth Fade” value to 750 as a starting point.
</p>
<pre>    a. This value controls how deep translucency is set at the waters edge.
    b. You can play around with this value to get the outcome you would like.
    c. We will combine this with the “Fresnel” parameter for easy fine tune adjustments
</pre>
<p>7. Connect the “Fresnel Parameter” to the “BaseReflectFractionIn” of the “Fresnel”
</p><p>8. Connect the “Fresnel to the “1-x”
</p><p>9. Connect the “1-x” to the “B” of one “Multiply”
</p><p>10. Connect the “Depth Fade” to the “A” of that “Multiply”
</p><p>11. Connect that “Multiply” to the “B” of the second “Multiply”
</p><p>12. Connect the “Refraction Parameter” to the “A” of the “Multiply”
</p><p>13. Connect the final “Multiply” to the “Opacity” pin and “Refraction” of our Material.
</p><p>14. Now create a new external “Multiply” which we will combine with the normal section.
</p>
<div class="thumb tleft"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:884px;"><a href="/File:OpacityandRefraction.PNG" class="image"><img alt="" src="https://d26ilriwvtzlb.cloudfront.net/4/4a/OpacityandRefraction.PNG" width="882" height="442" class="thumbimage" /></a>  <div class="thumbcaption">Opacity and Refraction Section</div></div></div>
<p><br clear="all" />
</p><p><br />
</p>
<h4><span class="mw-headline" id="Normal_Maps_Section">Normal Maps Section</span></h4>
<p>In this section we will be taking the Normal texture maps “T_Ground_Grass” from the starter content and panning them across one another to get our ripples/waves.
</p>
<pre>    <i>The larger the size of your ripples the less fine your reflections become because the larger waves will distort the images.</i> 
    <i>On the opposite spectrum, the finer your ripples the clearer your reflections because you draw closer to a smooth surface (like glass).</i>
</pre>
<p>1. Drag in the two Normal texture samples you downloaded into your material editor.
</p><p>2. Create three “Multiply” nodes.
</p><p>3. Create an “Add” node.
</p><p>4. Create a “Divide” node.
</p><p>5. Create a “ComponentMask” node with R and G selected.
</p><p>6. Create an “Absolute World Position” node.
</p><p>7. Create a “Constant3Vector” node and set its value to a color not exactly white, but close. 
</p><p>8. Create two “Panner” nodes.
</p>
<pre>    a. Set the “Coordinate” of first node
       i. “Speed X” to 0.03
       ii. “Speed Y” to -0.02
    b. Set the “Coordinate” of second node
       i. “Speed X” to -0.015
       ii. “Speed Y” to 0.01 
</pre>
<p>9. Create three regular “Constant” nodes and convert these to parameters.
</p>
<pre>    a. Label one “Overall Wave Size”
       i. Set its “Default Value” to 1200
    b. Label another “Smaller Ripples”
       i. Set its value to 0.75
    c. Label another “Larger Ripples”
       i. Set its value to 0.25
</pre>
<p>10. Connect the “Absolute World Position” to the “A” of the “Divide”
</p><p>11. Connect the “Overall Wave Size” to the “B” of the “Divide”
</p><p>12. Connect the “Divide” outcome to the “Mask (R G)”
</p><p>13. Connect the “ComponentMask” to the first “Panner” and second “Panner” into the “Coordinate” pins
</p><p>14. Connect the first “Panner” to the “A” of a “Multiply”
</p><p>15. Connect the “Small Ripples” to the “B” of the “Multiply”
</p><p>16. Connect the second “Panner” to the “A” of another “Multiply”
</p><p>17. Connect the “Larger Ripples” to the “B” of that “Multiply”
</p><p>18. Take the outcome of one “Multiply” and connect it to one of the Normal texture samples, and do the same for the other.
</p><p>19. Connect the two normal texture samples to the “Add” node of “A” and “B.”
</p><p>20. Connect the “Add” node to the “A” of the last “Multiply” and the “Constant3Vector” to the “B”
</p><p>21. Connect the final “Multiply” to the “Normal” of our material
</p>
<pre>    a. Also connect this to the “Normal” pin of the “Fresnel” in our diffuse section
    b. Finally connect this to the external “Multiply” to the “B” with our Opacity and Refraction section
</pre>
<div class="thumb tleft"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:1483px;"><a href="/File:WaveSizes.PNG" class="image"><img alt="" src="https://d26ilriwvtzlb.cloudfront.net/9/9f/WaveSizes.PNG" width="1481" height="431" class="thumbimage" /></a>  <div class="thumbcaption">Normal Section</div></div></div>
<p><br />
</p>
<h4><span class="mw-headline" id="Wave_Speed_and_Height_Section">Wave Speed and Height Section</span></h4>
<p>This section really gives the dynamic feel to our water by adding a wave surge and speed in between each rise and fall. 
This is an attempt to simulate the rise and fall of water rushing onto a shoreline and receding back into itself.
</p>
<pre>    This is an optional section but really adds a bit more realism and life to our water material.
</pre>
<p>1. Create two “Multiply” nodes.
</p><p>2. Create three “Add” nodes.
</p><p>3. Create two “Sine” nodes.
</p><p>4. Create two “ConstantBiasScale” nodes.
</p><p>5. Create an “Append” node.
</p><p>6. Create a “Constant2Vector” node.
</p><p>7. Create a “Time” node.
</p><p>8. Create an “Absolute World Position” node.
</p><p>9. Create three “Constant” nodes and convert them to parameters
</p>
<pre>    a. Name one “Wave Speed”
       i. Set the value to 2.5
    b. Name one “Speed and Surge Divisor”
       i. Set the value to 1600
    c. Name one “Wave Height Surge”
       i. Set the value to 65
</pre>
<p>10. Create a “Divide” node.
</p><p>11. Finally create two “ComponentMask” nodes.
</p>
<pre>    a. Set one mask to “R” i.e. “Mask ( R )”
    b. Set the other to mask “G” or “Mask ( G )”
</pre>
<p>12. Connect the end “Multiply” node to the “World Position Offset” of your material.
</p><p>13. Use the image posted below as reference on how to connect it all together.
</p>
<div class="thumb tleft"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:1469px;"><a href="/File:WaveSpeedandHeight.PNG" class="image"><img alt="" src="https://d26ilriwvtzlb.cloudfront.net/0/06/WaveSpeedandHeight.PNG" width="1467" height="356" class="thumbimage" /></a>  <div class="thumbcaption">Wave Speed and Height Section</div></div></div>
<p><br clear="all" />
</p>
<h4><span class="mw-headline" id="External_Multiply_and_Constants">External Multiply and Constants</span></h4>
<p>Here are the external “Multiply” nodes and constants in case you needed clarification on where they go as well.
</p>
<div class="thumb tleft"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:1352px;"><a href="/File:MultipliesandConstants.PNG" class="image"><img alt="" src="https://d26ilriwvtzlb.cloudfront.net/6/66/MultipliesandConstants.PNG" width="1350" height="578" class="thumbimage" /></a>  <div class="thumbcaption">External Connections</div></div></div>
<p><br clear="all" />
</p>
<pre>    Save and Apply material to a plane in your scene to observe your new water shader!
</pre>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="External_Links">External Links</span></h3>
<p>Here is the final shader in case you had troubles or would like to skip the tutorial altogether:
</p>
<pre>    <a href="/File:WaterShader.zip" title="File:WaterShader.zip">File:WaterShader.zip</a>
</pre>
